Date:  0/0/1949
Source:  Dictionary of Slang Addenda
Author:  PARTRiDGE
Vol / Page:  1078
Edition:
Quote:  Hook one's bait (or mutton). To depart; to decamp, make off: New Zealand and Australian: C. 20. Baker. Elaboration of Hook it.
Notes:

Date:  0/0/1966
Source:  English Language in Aust. & NZ, The
Author:  TURNER
Vol / Page:  177
Edition:
Quote:  Some expressions that have been claimed for New Zealand are at the rate of knots `very fast',

hook your mutton `clear out', have the wood on `have an advantage over' and the oaths

Blimey Charlie and (By) Christchurch (obviously a neat save suggested by the place name).
Notes:

Date:  0/0/1988
Source:  Dictionary of Kiwi Slang, A
Author:  McGiLL
Vol / Page:  57
Edition:
Quote:   hook your mutton clear out, similar to `slinging your hook'; eg `Let's hook our mutton, there's no welcome here, fellas.'
